National Security Advisor Jake Sullivan recently had a discussion with Caribbean Community (CARICOM) Secretary General Irwin LaRocque and leaders from CARICOM member states. Sullivan reiterated the Biden-Harris administration's commitment to collaborating with the Caribbean region on various issues such as managing the COVID-19 pandemic, promoting economic recovery, addressing climate change, and enhancing regional democracy and security. Building on Secretary of State Blinken's virtual roundtable with CARICOM Foreign Ministers on April 21, Sullivan suggested regular high-level engagement between the United States and CARICOM, including a meeting between the President and CARICOM heads of State. The call involved the participation of the Prime Minister and Foreign Minister of St. Vincent & the Grenadines, foreign ministers from Antigua & Barbuda, the Bahamas, Belize, the Commonwealth of Dominica, Grenada, Guyana, Jamaica, Saint Lucia, St. Kitts & Nevis, Suriname, Trinidad & Tobago, as well as the Permanent Secretary of Barbados and the Premier of Monserrat.